english:
  title: Epitaph and Preface for Minister Kwon Kong, Lord of Gilchang, with the Posthumous Name Ikpyeong
  author: Shin Suk-ju
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I have heard it said that when roots run deep, the branches must flourish abundantly, and when the source flows from distant springs, the stream must run long—such is the eternal principle of things. My friend Minister Kwon, whose personal name was Yeom and courtesy name was Jeonggyeong, came from a family originally surnamed Kim. In the eighth year of Yongping under the Ming Emperor Mingdi, in the year of Eul-chuk, Alji was born in Sirim and took the surname Kim—a matter of extraordinary significance. His descendants, together with the Park and Seok clans, took turns ruling as kings of Silla. When his descendant named Haeng came to guard Andong, he was recognized by the founder of Goryeo and received the surname Kwon, with Andong as his fief. His official rank rose to the Three Han Wall-Standing Triple Grand Commandant and Grand Preceptor. After nine generations came the Privy Counselor Soobyeong, whose crystalline virtue shone forth in the world. The Privy Counselor fathered the Hanlin Scholar Wie, who first attained the examination degree and became known for his knowledge of ritual propriety. The scholar fathered the Vice Premier Dan, who governed four districts and served as inspector of five provinces, everywhere earning praise for his incorruptibility and impartiality. He was given the epithet "Dream Hermitage" and the posthumous name "Cultivated and Pure." Cultivated and Pure fathered the Minister of the Imperial Household Pu, whose merit and virtue stood foremost in his age. He was enfeoffed as Prince of Yongga—which is another name for Andong. He bore the epithet "Chrysanthemum Studio" and the posthumous name "Culturally Correct." His sons Ko and Hui successively inherited the enfeoffment through three generations. Hui fathered Geun, who through the study of Principle opened the minds of our Eastern people. His moral character and literary works towered above those of former worthies, and the Hongwu Emperor of the Ming, upon seeing him once, held him in such esteem that his name resounded throughout the Middle Kingdom. He rose to the rank of Merit Official for Transmitting Loyalty and Assisting Authority as a Founding Strategist, Vice Premier of the State Council, and Prince of Gilchang. He was given the epithet "Sunny Village" and the posthumous name "Culturally Loyal." He received posthumous enfeoffment as Left Premier with the merit designation "Purely Loyal, Accumulating Virtue, Supplementing Blessings." Culturally Loyal fathered the one named Ti, formerly called Tao, who inherited his father's literary distinction and rose to head of the examination. He was deeply trusted by our King Sejong and rose to the position of Right Vice Premier. He bore the epithet "Stopping Studio" and the posthumous name "Culturally Bright." He received posthumous enfeoffment as Commander of the State Council and Minister of Personnel with the merit designation "Purely Loyal, Accumulating Virtue, Upholding Righteousness, Supplementing Blessings"—this was the Minister's father. Both received posthumous honor through the Minister's achievements. His mother was Lady Jeonggyeong, daughter of Yi Joon, Inspector of the Court Provisions Bureau.

    The Minister was born on the fifth lunar month, day Eulmi, in the year Byeongsin of the Yonglo reign. From the eighth year of Yongping under the Han Emperor Mingdi in the year Eul-chuk to the present, more than a thousand years have passed. Through successive generations there has been manifest excellence and beautiful virtue, with his descendants serving in high office—is this not what is meant by roots running deep so that branches flourish, and sources flowing far so that streams run long?

    The Minister loved reading from childhood and possessed a broad, cultivated spirit with ambitious visions and extraordinary strategies. He carried books on his back seeking out famous mountains and ancient sites, traveling everywhere without exception, always accompanied by Korea's Han Zijun of Sangdang. Wherever they went, they would linger to read and compose writings to express their feelings, never seeking official position. Until his thirty-fifth year, he remained carefree, roaming as though through lakes and mountains. Friends urged him to take the civil examination, and in a single attempt he successively took first place in all three sections. At that time, our present sovereign was dwelling in his princely residence, having received the imperial mandate to annotate the Military Classics. The Minister became his attendant, and the sovereign, recognizing his great talent, treated him with exceptional favor. At that time, treacherous officials wielded power and the state trembled precariously. The Minister first proposed a grand strategy and recommended Han Zijun as well. The sovereign entrusted both men with planning and mobilization. They gathered the loyal-hearted and righteous, combing through the realm like one arranging hair, weeding out sedition like hoeing grain, and thus quelled the great rebellion. For these merits, he received the title "Merit Official for Transmitting Loyalty, Safeguarding the State, Cooperating in Strategy, and Pacifying Turmoil," and when the sovereign ascended the throne, he also received the title "Merit Official for Acting in Concord and Assisting in Government," both ranked as supreme merits.

    Initially, treacherous factions had woven their web, with internal and external forces alternating in sedition, and tyranny blazed fiercely. Yet this was accomplished without a single soldier or blade of steel—through loyalty and righteousness alone. Though heaven's mandate turned and the true sovereign responded to destiny's call, had not the Minister's counsel and moral authority facilitated and supported these events, how could the loyal and righteous have responded as one, and this clear and peaceful realm been achieved in so short a time, ensuring the stability of the ancestral shrine and state? That he ranked foremost among both the Pacification and Government merits is indeed fitting.

    Leaping over the usual ranks, he was promoted to Vice Director of Royal Decrees. By the law of our realm, those who pass the civil examination are honored with a banquet celebrating their parents' virtue. When the Minister held such a banquet for his revered mother, her crane-white hair graced the high seat while grand officials filled the entrance. The sovereign himself, as the Premier, attended and personally offered felicitations to the lady—such glory illuminated the entire age. He was appointed Vice Minister of Personnel and enfeoffed as Prince of Gilchang—Gilchang being another name for the Andong region.

    When the sovereign ascended the throne, the Minister was sent to Beijing to receive the imperial edict of appointment. Sukju accompanied him. The Minister possessed such noble bearing and dignified appearance that in his presence one perceived virtue and magnanimity. The Chinese people could not but love, admire, and honor him. He successfully obtained the edict and returned. The sovereign, delighted, bestowed upon all members of the delegation the title "Merit Official of Original Followers." The Minister was promoted to Grand Master for Distant Attendants, Minister of Personnel, Grand Scholar of the Jiphyeonjeon Institute, and concurrent Director of Princely Instruction. He was successively promoted to Grand Commandant, Commander of the State Council, and concurrent Minister of Personnel.

    The Minister had suffered from deficient qi since childhood and often disliked the burdens of office. At this time, he requested retirement from active service. The sovereign personally wrote in reply: "Our relationship transcends what might be expressed as compatible minds and harmonious virtue—heaven itself brought us forth. Had you harbored even the slightest selfish desire, or I the merest craving for personal gain, would we have cast ourselves into water and flame, forgotten our wives and children, sworn oaths to heaven and earth, and thus pacified the chaos? That we have achieved this day is because you are truly the architect of these accomplishments. Now seeing your intention to retire to mountains and streams brings me wonder that knows no end. How can you shed the burden heaven has placed upon you?" Thus he was appointed Right Vice Premier. Soon after, he was appointed Grand Commandant and Minister of the Right, then promoted to Left Premier.

    At the outset of the Pacification, in dismissing treacherous officials and promoting the capable and worthy, in straightening what was crooked and eliminating confusion, the Minister truly opened the sovereign's mind and provided secret counsel. As Premier, he was magnanimous and at ease, delighting in simplicity. He was fair-minded, stern yet composed, devoted to maintaining established laws while preserving their essential principles and overlooking minor details. Before his plans could be fully realized, he eventually petitioned to retire from office due to illness. Yet in all military and state matters of importance, the sovereign sent messengers to consult him, and envoys bringing provisions and inquiries came without ceasing. As his illness worsened, the palace physicians attended to his medicines and the imperial kitchen provided continuous care—nothing was left undone.

    In the first month of the second year of Seonghwa, on the day Gapsin, he passed away. The sovereign, deeply stricken, ceased eating and suspended court proceedings. The gifts of condolence exceeded measure, and the state undertook the funeral arrangements. Both officials and common people mourned in profound sorrow, with lamentations filling the streets, while friends rushed about weeping in anguish.

    I had often competed with the Minister in aspiring to retire, wishing to escape the surfeiting of rank and office. Yet he was the first to truly implement this—slipping free from the dust of confusion to preserve his spirit in serene purity. I thought he would surely enjoy long life in such retirement, yet fate brought this upon us. Truly, heaven's way is difficult to fathom.

    When the Minister first received his dismissal, the decree arrived at night. I rose and read the imperial rescript, then sat awaiting dawn. The Minister indeed sent me several poems in jest, saying:
    "From now on I envy not the Minister of Han—
    On a single horse by West Lake I wander alone."

    Seeing these verses, I was bewildered and lost. We had once made a pact to enjoy spring together each year. The Minister's residence was situated at the foot of South Mountain, overlooking the city, with peach and plum blossoms flowering in profusion, their red and white splendor brilliant before the eyes. We held that spring celebration once, but afterward, year after year I was sent on inspection tours of the northern garrison, and when I returned there were urgent matters to attend to. Moreover, the Minister fell ill, and we never renewed our spring outings. Now I too have obtained retirement from office and cast off my heavy burdens to wander at leisure—yet the Minister has gone, and I can no longer follow him in his wanderings. With him the season of friendship has passed away. Alas!

    The Minister married the daughter of the Prince of Tieseong, a woman of the Li clan, granddaughter of Minister Li Eom, and was enfeoffed as the Lady of Ningyuan. They had two sons and eight daughters. The eldest son, Geol, served as Merit Guard and Escorts Guard. The second son, Geon, was still young. The eldest daughter married Han Seoggwi, Prince of Cheongwon, a Merit Official for Transmitting Loyalty in the Pacification. The second married Right Defender Bak Sahwa. The third married Inspector Shin Eknyon. The fourth married Guard Namyi, but predeceased the Minister. The fifth married Director of the Abundant Granary Kim Suhaeng. The youngest remained small.

    From the founding ancestor through the Minister, the blessings of his lineage have only grown greater. Why then was his life cut short when fortune had become so abundant? I have heard that those who give generously receive generous returns. The Minister's cultivation of virtue and dispensing of blessings have not yet ceased, so that the flourishing of his branches and the length of his stream have already been proven—perhaps they shall yet flow even further?

    In the fourth lunar month, on day Jeongyu, he was buried in Mibeop Valley west of Chungju, in a plot adjacent to his father's grave. The following autumn, my nephew the Prince of Cheongwon approached me requesting that I compose an inscription on stone to transmit the Minister's merits and virtue to posterity.

    Alas, the Minister's official career and accomplishments, the sovereign's deep affection and patronage, already have their place in the national records, which I need not elaborate here. His filial piety and brotherly respect within the household, his treatment of kinfolk and friends—each perfectly embodied their proper measure—are so extensive that even woven texts could not fully contain them. I shall merely sketch the outline, ultimately expressing only the sorrow and love that fills my heart.

    Sukju was of similar age to the Minister, and from youth we pursued studies together. We would often jest with one another, boasting that we would write epitaphs for each other's graves. Now this has indeed come to pass. If those in the underworld could rise and speak, what would they say of this turn of events? Alas, the pain of this loss knows no bounds.

    *The Inscription reads:*

    *Distant was the Minister's beginning,*
    *Emerging first from Sirim,*
    *In Goryeo's dawning age,*
    *From Kim transformed to Kwon.*
    *Blessings accumulated, fortune's light descended,*
    *High ranks and robes in succession appeared.*
    *Some by merit and virtue,*
    *Some through literary grace,*
    *Beauty inherited, fragrance transmitted,*
    *To the Minister grew and expanded.*
    *Roots deep so branches spread wide,*
    *Sources far so streams flow long.*
    *When the Minister first aroused his spirit,*
    *Books alone were his business,*
    *Lofty and unbound,*
    *Wandering through lakes and mountains.*
    *In one attempt three sections mastered—*
    *His deeds expansive, his traces remarkable.*
    *The great gentleman should be*
    *Just as this.*
    *Treacherous officials stole power,*
    *Wantonly wielding their sway,*
    *Playing with the mechanisms of rule,*
    *Calamity reached the altars.*
    *Yet holy heaven watched our land,*
    *And gave us a sage sovereign,*
    *Sending worthy counsel to aid*
    *And restore what was lost.*
    *Heaven's mandate turned, hearts aligned—*
    *Like moths to flame, the wicked fell.*
    *He cut away treachery,*
    *Selected and elevated talent,*
    *Separating confusion into parts,*
    *Opening what was blocked and stagnant.*
    *He drove back their theft and robbery,*
    *Unfolding our land's blessing.*
    *In the council chamber he rose to highest rank,*
    *Spreading moral transformation far and wide.*
    *The sovereign sought his counsel like consulting the oracle,*
    *The realm leaned upon him as on a cornerstone.*
    *Why does heaven not grieve,*
    *Yet swiftly snatched his years away?*
    *Our friendship was genuine affection,*
    *Bonded close as glue and lacquer.*
    *Missing you, mourning you—*
    *In this both public duty and private heart join.*
    *Alas, O Minister,*
    *Does it end here?*
    *Death and life transform,*
    *The passing seasons do not stay.*
    *Spring departs from the eastern hills,*
    *And I alone weep by the western city.*
    *Recording virtue, inscribing merit—*
    *I blush at my inadequate brush.*
    *I can only set down heartfelt truth*
    *To show those who come after.*
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Alji (閼智) was the legendary founder of the Silla kingdom, said to have been born miraculously. The surname Kim (金) derives from the gold-colored light surrounding his birth.
  - key: ''
    value: 'The ''three sections'' (三場) refer to the three-part civil examination system used in Korea: policy questions, literary composition, and oral examination.'
  - key: ''
    value: Sikrim (始林) is the legendary forest where Alji was born in Silla mythology.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Military Classics' (武經) here refers to military strategic texts, reflecting the prince's preparation for governance.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'West Lake' evokes the famous scenic region near Hangzhou, associated with retirement and contentment in Chinese and Korean literary tradition.
  - key: ''
    value: The epitaph's closing verses use the traditional Chinese poetic device of cataloging the subject's virtues through connected imagery—deep roots, distant sources, flowering branches—to suggest the enduring nature of his legacy.
